The Whitefield School
July 10 at 1:03 PM ·

A Note From Ms. Brady Regarding Middle School Field Hockey

Student Athletes,

I wanted to make you aware of some opportunities that you will have this summer to be involved with your athletic teams and coaches. Coaches are starting to set up summer training sessions.

During this time, it is crucial that we follow all guidelines from the state and the New Hampshire Interscholastic Association (NHIAA). Attached to this email is our district’s return to play guidelines.

All student athletes and parents must complete the release form prior to starting any summer sessions. If you have any questions please contact Ms. Brady at kbrady@sau36.org.

Summer Training Sessions Schedule:

Field Hockey - Monday (6:00 pm - 7:30 pm), Wednesdays 6:00 pm - 7:30 pm) (Lancaster Elementary School)

Please remember to come prepared to the training sessions as the school buildings will not be open.

post_text:
Here's another sneak peek of some of the new equipment provided by the System of Care office! The Spartan Learning Commons is now home to 60 of these unique chairs! The Learning Commons is made up of three classrooms and is used by Title I, Special Education, ELOs, and online learning (which includes credit recovery, VLACS, Early College, and other online platforms).

These chairs allow students to sit either in a traditional way or by turning around and using the back arm rest to support their bodies. Students choose the way they sit based on their current mood. The chairs also have ultra-quiet wheel casters to allow students to get into small groups or wheel up to a teacher without the distraction of dragging chairs.

post_text:
Friday Mindfulness break from the SoC office: Relaxing Breath (4-7-8)
To use the 4-7-8 technique, focus on the following breathing pattern: ... breathe in quietly through the nose for 4 seconds. Hold the breath for a count of 7 seconds. Exhale forcefully through the mouth, pursing the lips and making a "whoosh" sound, for 8 seconds (this can be done silently through your nose if you are around people and can't make noise).

shared_text:
Lancaster Elementary School
April 13 at 8:30 AM ·

Hello Families!

Starting this week, the 4th and 5th grade Lil' Spartans are going to challenge teachers, students, and the community at large to compete in an Attitude of Gratitude challenge! Research has shown that giving thanks to people makes them feel good, as well as ourselves! Let's give each other a little happiness!

This week's challenge to kick things off is to make a card, write a letter, draw a picture, color a paper, etc. to express our gratitude to medical workers. They are working hard to save lives and keep us safe.

Instead of mailing these, we would like to put this together in a video. Please snap a photo and send it to athibault@sau36.org by Friday April 17th.

Lancaster and LES show some gratitude to all the medical workers keeping us safe and helping us when we need it!

Starting this week, the 4th and 5th grade Lil' Spartans are going to challenge teachers, students, and the community at large to compete in an Attitude of Gratitude challenge! Research has shown that giving thanks to people makes them feel good, as well as ourselves! Let's give each other a little happiness!

This week's challenge to kick things off is to make a card, write a letter, draw a picture, color a paper, etc. to express our gratitude to medical workers. They are working hard to save lives and keep us safe.

Instead of mailing these, we would like to put this together in a video. Please snap a photo and send it to athibault@sau36.org by Friday April 17th.

Lancaster and LES show some gratitude to all the medical workers keeping us safe and helping us when we need it!

shared_text:
Lancaster Elementary School
March 24 at 12:15 PM ·

We love to hear and celebrate the positive!

"I’m sure you are getting many of these, and if not, you should be! I can’t say enough about Mr. Houle, Mrs. Fuller and Mrs. Caron during this transition to remote learning and our dive into the last few days. The communication, enthusiasm, flexibility, and support we have received is top-notch. We hear from them multiple times a day via video chat, phone calls, emails, and Class Dojo. In a time that could be extremely stressful for these children (and parents!), they have put us all at ease. They encourage out of the box learning, the kids remaining active, brain breaks and fun challenges. Kudos to your great staff!"

shared_text:
The Whitefield School
March 24 at 9:07 AM ·

Good Morning Pirates!

A Note From Mrs. Powers - Art Teacher (WES)

Wow, what a storm we got last night! Please have some fun this week, and make a sculpture with snow! Think of your three dimensional form from all angles and sides. Feel free to add any additional materials to enhance your work, such as leaves, sticks, rocks, or anything you can find outdoors!

You can make anything! A penguin, whale, fish, Disney character, anything that comes to mind! As long as you’re having fun, and exploring the three dimensions. Then share your photo with us, so we can see your creativity shine and share it with the community!

Please email your pictures (include family name) to apowers@sau36.org

post_text:
Clarification on meal delivery: Buses will be running their regular routes as if school was in session. Meals will be delivered to each student on that buses roster. If a student is not a bus student, the student was assigned to a bus route so that they would get their meal. All they need to do is stand at the bottom of their driveway where a bus would pass by to receive their meal. For those students that walk to a bus stop they will need to walk there to pick up their mail. If a student is driven to school all they need to do is stand at the bottom of their driveway and the bus will stop for them to receive their meal.
Buses depart Lancaster Elementary at 10am to begin deliveries.

post_text: From our System of Care office: Today is International Day of Happiness! This day seeks to celebrate and promote world happiness as a fundamental human goal. It recognizes the need for a more inclusive, equitable, and balanced approach to economic growth, one that promotes sustainable development, poverty eradication, happiness, and well-being of all people. Despite our current challenges, SAU 36 hopes you will find those moments today that make you happy.

REMINDER: Tomorrow there will be a Renovation and Redesign informational session at the Lancaster Elementary School at 6:30pm.
Additionally, The Rotary Club of Lancaster is kindly sponsoring an informational session at The Granite Grind on Main Street in Lancaster next Tuesday, February 25th, at 5pm. To RSVP for this event, email Roxanne Ball at rhball@sau36.org, or call (603)-837-9363.

White Mountains Regional High School
February 11 at 8:10 PM ·

Yesterday we had some educators from Springpoint, an educational consulting company, visit us to give feedback on our work with the Barr Foundation. They spoke with admin, teachers and students about life as a Spartan, and gave us an outsider’s perspective on the work we do here. It was a very meaningful visit, and we’re so thankful to have opportunities like this to help us improve!😆 #DoingHSDifferently #BarrFDN #ThisIsSparta

shared_text:
White Mountains Regional High School
February 10 at 5:12 PM ·

Happy #MotivationMonday ! There’s nothing more motivational & inspirational than our fellow Spartans’ successes! 2 of our senior athletes, Noah Dutkewych and Kevin Schanlaber, had amazingly successful competitions this past weekend!
Noah captured his 100th career win at the Plymouth wrestling tournament and Kevin won the NHIAA Division II indoor long jump title while setting a DII state record of 21 ft, 10.75in.
We’re so proud of our Spartans! Keep up the great work👏 #SpartanAthletics #Proud #MotovationMonday
(Photo 1 by Josh Spaulding, Photo 2 by Nicole Hayden)
